# coralReef Standards

## Language & Toolchain
- Rust 2024 edition, `rust-version = "1.85"`. No C/C++/Python in production.
- `clippy::pedantic` + `clippy::nursery` — ZERO warnings. `cargo clippy --all-features -- -D warnings`.
- `#![forbid(unsafe_code)]` on all crate roots except `coral-driver` (hardware ioctl).
- `#![warn(missing_docs)]` on library crates. Doctests count as tests.

## License
- `AGPL-3.0-only` everywhere. First line of every `.rs` file: `// SPDX-License-Identifier: AGPL-3.0-only`

## Code Size & Style
- No file > 1000 lines. Split into cohesive submodules.
- No TODO/FIXME/HACK in committed `.rs` code. Track in handoffs.
- No `.unwrap()` in library code. Use `Result<T, E>` + `thiserror`. `.expect()` with reason is acceptable.
- No commented-out code. Git remembers.
- Semantic naming: functions say what they do, variables say what they hold.

## IPC (JSON-RPC + tarpc)
- JSON-RPC 2.0 primary (TCP/HTTP external, Unix socket local). tarpc optional high-perf.
- Semantic method names: `{domain}.{operation}[.{variant}]` (e.g. `shader.compile.wgsl`).
- Primals never import each other's code. All coordination via JSON-RPC.
- Discover by capability, not by primal name. No hardcoded primal names in production.

## Binary Architecture (UniBin → ecoBin)
- Single binary per primal with clap subcommands, `--help`, `--version`.
- Pure Rust dependencies. Prefer `rustix` over `libc`. No openssl/ring/vendor SDKs.
- Platform-agnostic IPC: Unix socket primary, TCP fallback for non-Unix.
- Hardcoded paths use env var override with sane default.

## Zero-Copy & Performance
- `bytes::Bytes` for IPC payloads. Minimize `.clone()`.
- `unsafe` only in `coral-driver` with SAFETY comments on every block.

## Testing
- `cargo test --all-features` — zero failures.
- Named tolerances for numerical comparisons (no magic numbers).
- Target 90% coverage (llvm-cov). Hardware tests gated behind `#[ignore]`.
